ar, 23 Mar, 24 Mar, 25 Mar, 26 Mar, 27 Mar, 28 Mar, 29 Mar, 30 Mar, 31 Mar, 1 Apr, 2 Apr, 3 Apr, 4 Apr, 5 Apr, 6 Apr, 7 Apr, 8 Apr, 9 Apr, 10 Apr, 11 Apr, 12 Apr\n| yAxisTitle = No. of new tested\n| y1 = 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 475, 0, 0, 182, 77, 0, 75, 139, 231, 0, 742, 624, 384, 276, 503, 442, 520, 303, 3311, 631, 1052, 1256, 1401, 1842, 1532, 1455, 2210, 1797, 1643, 1551, 1955, 1874, 3174, 4435, 2531, 2364, 2591, 3629, 4595, 3628, 3842, 3056\n| legend=Legend\n| showValues=offset:2\n| y1Title = Tested per day\n| yGrid = | xGrid = \n}}\n\n== Statistics ==\n<div style=\"max-height: 500px; overflow-y: scroll; padding-right: 20px\">\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Romania medical cases}}\n</div>\n\nAs of March 18, a plurality (29%) of COVID-19 cases were people between the ages of 40 and 49. Of the patients, 51% are women, 44% are men, and children \u2013 5%.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hotnews.ro/stiri-coronavirus-23734261-infografic-varste-romanii-care-imbolnavit-covid-19-varsta-medie-pacientilor-41-ani.htm |title=INFOGRAFIC Ce v\u00e2rste au rom\u00e2nii care s-au \u00eemboln\u0103vit de COVID-19. V\u00e2rsta medie a pacien\u021bilor - 41 de ani |last=H., I. |date=18 March 2020 |website=HotNews.ro}}</ref>\n\n== Response by sector ==\n=== Economics ===\n[[File:Emergency measures COVID 19 Romania.jpg|thumb|200px|\"Please  keep your distance\" notice in a Bucharest supermarket, 28 March 2020.]]\n[[File:Carrefour Brasov shelves, Covid.jpg|thumb|200px|Flour almost sold out, Bra\u0219ov, 14 March]]  \nDuring the second week of March, the [[Bucharest Stock Exchange]] recorded losses on all five trading sessions, the main index BET collapsing with 17.6%, the steepest decline since December 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.zf.ro/burse-fonduri-mutuale/saptamana-de-cosmar-pentru-bursa-romaneasca-prabusire-de-17-6-inca-nu-stim-daca-socul-economic-va-dura-1-luna-2-luni-sau-mai-mult-18982027 |title=S\u0103pt\u0103m\u00e2na de co\u0219mar pentru bursa rom\u00e2neasc\u0103: pr\u0103bu\u0219ire de 17,6%. \"\u00cenc\u0103 nu \u0219tim dac\u0103 \u0219ocul economic va dura 1 lun\u0103, 2 luni, sau mai mult\" |last=Popescu, Liviu |date=14 March 2020 |website=Ziarul Financiar}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, the [[National Bank of Romania]] announced a reference rate of 4.8242 [[Romanian leu|lei]]/[[euro]], a historical maximum for the single European currency against the leu.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://incont.stirileprotv.ro/cursuri/moneda-unica-marcheaza-un-nou-maxim-istoric-in-raport-cu-leul-c-curs-a-anuntat-bnr-pentru-euro.html |title=Moneda unic\u0103 marcheaz\u0103 un nou maxim istoric \u00een raport cu leul. Ce curs a anun\u021bat BNR pentru euro |date=16 March 2020 |website=inCont.ro}}</ref> The leu continued its depreciation, reaching a maximum of 4.8448 lei/euro on March 17.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.economica.net/curs-bnr-azi-17-martie-2020-leu-euro-dolar-franc-elvetian-curs-valutar-interbancar-robor-aur_181227.html |title=A doua zi consecutiv\u0103 \u00een care leul atinge minimul istoric \u00een fa\u021ba euro. Curs BNR 17.03.2020: 4,8448 lei/euro |date=17 March 2020 |website=Economica.net}}</ref>\n\n=== Education ===\nOn March 9, interim Prime-minister [[Ludovic Orban]] announced the closure of all schools between March 11 and 22. The measure targeted all kindergartens, primary, secondary and high schools in Romania, both public and private, according to Education Minister {{ill|Monica Anisie|ro}}.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.romania-insider.com/romania-closes-schools-coronavirus-march-2020 |title=Update: Romania closes all schools to fight coronavirus outbreak |date=9 March 2020 |website=Romania-Insider.com}}</ref> The decision affects 3.5 million students.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.libertatea.ro/stiri/bucurestenii-inchiderea-scolilor-coronavirus-2909216 |title=Cum se adapteaz\u0103 bucure\u0219tenii la \u00eenchiderea \u0219colilor \u0219i ce p\u0103rere au despre \u00eenmul\u021birea cazurilor de coronavirus |last=Stanciu |first=Daniel |last2=Nistor |first2=Cosmin |date=11 March 2020 |website=Libertatea |last3=Capoeanu |first3=George}}</ref> Likewise, several universities in the major student centres suspended their courses. These include the [[University of Bucharest]], the [[Bucharest Academy of Economic Studies]], the [[Politehnica University of Bucharest]], the [[Babe\u0219-Bolyai University]], the [[West University of Timi\u0219oara]], etc.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.libertatea.ro/stiri/universitatea-bucuresti-isi-suspenda-cursurile-2908415 |title=UPDATE. Universitatea din Bucure\u0219ti \u0219i ASE \u00ee\u0219i suspend\u0103 cursurile p\u00e2n\u0103 la sf\u00e2r\u0219itul lunii |last=Radu, Cristina |date=11 March 2020 |website=Libertatea}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mediafax.ro/coronavirus/cea-mai-mare-universitate-din-tara-ubb-suspenda-cursurile-pana-in-22-martie-18959559 |title=Cea mai mare universitate din \u021bar\u0103, UBB, suspend\u0103 cursurile p\u00e2n\u0103 \u00een 22 martie |last=M\u0103gr\u0103dean, Vasile |date=10 March 2020 |website=Mediafax}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pressalert.ro/2020/03/se-suspenda-cursurile-si-la-universitatea-de-vest-din-timisoara-din-cauza-coronavirus/ |title=Se suspend\u0103 cursurile \u0219i la Universitatea de Vest din Timi\u0219oara, din cauza COVID 19 |last=M\u00ee\u021b, Adriana |date=11 March 2020 |website=pressalert.ro}}</ref> Furthermore, Anisie announced that, as a measure of prevention and control of the illnesses with COVID-19 in schools, the Ministry of Education had decided to suspend all county and regional school olympiads, as well as sports competitions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.agerpres.ro/educatie-stiinta/2020/03/09/mec-olimpiadele-scolare-judetene-si-regionale-precum-si-concursurile-sportive-suspendate--462247 |title=MEC: Olimpiadele \u015fcolare jude\u0163ene \u015fi regionale, precum \u015fi concursurile sportive - suspendate |last=AGERPRES |website=www.agerpres.ro |language=ro |access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\nThe show ''Tele\u0219coal\u0103'' (Teleschool), announced by the Ministry of Education and dedicated to the students who stay at home during the period when the schools are closed, started on [[TVR 2]] on March 16, at 9 a.m. Students can follow, from Monday to Friday, [[mathematics]], [[Romanian language|Romanian]], [[biology]], [[history]] and [[geography]] classes.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://mbl.hotnews.ro/stire/23718809 |title=TVR: Tele\u0219coala pentru elevii care stau acas\u0103 \u00eencepe pe 16 martie - Hotnews Mobile |website=mbl.hotnews.ro |access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://mobile.hotnews.ro/stire/23727012 |title=Tele\u0218coala a fost LIVE VIDEO pe ecrane \u0219i pe site-ul TVR+. ORARUL complet al cursurilor din prima s\u0103pt\u0103m\u00e2n\u0103 - Hotnews Mobile |website=mobile.hotnews.ro |access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, Anisie announced that schools would remain closed while the state of emergency was in place, at least until after the [[Easter]] holidays.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.digi24.ro/stiri/actualitate/educatie/ministrul-educatiei-scolile-raman-inchise-pana-dupa-paste-cat-e-anuntata-starea-de-urgenta-1276054 |title=Ministrul Educa\u021biei: \u0218colile r\u0103m\u00e2n \u00eenchise p\u00e2n\u0103 dup\u0103 Pa\u0219te, c\u00e2t e anun\u021bat\u0103 starea de urgen\u021b\u0103 |website=www.digi24.ro |language=ro |access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://mbl.hotnews.ro/stire/23726531 |title=Monica Anisie, ministrul Educa\u021biei: \u0218colile r\u0103m\u00e2n \u00eenchise p\u00e2n\u0103 dup\u0103 Pa\u0219te, c\u00e2t e anun\u021bat\u0103 starea de urgen\u021b\u0103 - Hotnews Mobile |website=mbl.hotnews.ro |access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\nOn April 1, in response to a [[fake news]] story which had gained traction on [[social media]] and was being destributed on [[WhatsApp]]<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://m.ziare.com/scoala/ministerul-educatiei-dezminte-un-fake-news-care-circula-pe-whatsapp-cursurile-nu-se-reiau-pe-6-aprilie-vom-face-denunt-penal-1604511 |title=Ministerul Educatiei dezminte un fake news, care circula pe Whatsapp: Cursurile nu se reiau pe 6 aprilie! Vom face denunt penal |work=Ziare.com |access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.romaniatv.net/scoli-inchise-pana-pe-6-aprilie-fake-news-in-mediul-online-ministerul-educatiei-precizari-de-ulti_515528.html |title=\u015eCOLI \u00ceNCHISE p\u00e2n\u0103 pe 6 aprilie, FAKE NEWS \u00een mediul online. Ministerul Educa\u0163iei, preciz\u0103ri de ultim\u0103 or\u0103 |date=2020-04-01 |website=romaniatv.net |access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>, saying that students would have to return to school in less than a week, Anisie and the Ministry of Education issued an official statement condemning the spread of false information and promised to provide in the next few days the date for the re-opening of schools, as well as the national examinations.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.digi24.ro/stiri/actualitate/document-fals-cu-privire-la-modificarea-structurii-anului-scolar-2019-2020-distribuit-online-reactia-ministerului-educatiei-1284871 |title=Document fals cu privire la modificarea structurii anului \u0219colar 2019-2020, distribuit online. Reac\u021bia Ministerului Educa\u021biei |website=www.digi24.ro |language=ro |access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.libertatea.ro/stiri/ministerul-educatiei-demonteaza-un-fake-news-care-circula-online-cursurile-nu-se-reiau-pe-6-aprilie-vom-face-denunt-penal-2936604 |title=Ministerul Educa\u0163iei demonteaz\u0103 un fake news care circul\u0103 online: \"Cursurile nu se reiau pe 6 aprilie. Vom face denun\u0163 penal\" |date=2020-04-01 |website=Libertatea |language=ro |access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.realitatea.net/stiri/actual/ministerul-educatiei-demonteaza-un-fake-news-ce-se-intampla-cu-anul-scolar_5e7fcda91773ac0fd00c0fa2 |title=Ministerul Educa\u021biei demonteaz\u0103 un fake news: Ce se \u00eent\u00e2mpl\u0103 cu anul \u0219colar |website=REALITATEA.NET |language=ro |access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n=== Sport ===\nThe [[Romanian Football Federation]] and the [[Romanian Handball Federation]] decided to suspend all matches until 31 March.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.digisport.ro/fotbal/pandemia-de-coronavirus-a-pus-lacat-pe-fotbalul-romanesc-frf-a-suspendat-toate-meciurile-810522 |title=Pandemia de coronavirus a pus \"lac\u0103t\" pe fotbalul rom\u00e2nesc! FRF a suspendat toate meciurile |date=12 March 2020 |website=Digi Sport}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://realitateasportiva.net/frh-anunta-ca-toate-competitiile-pe-plan-intern-au-fost-suspendate/ |title=FRH anun\u021b\u0103 c\u0103 toate competi\u021biile pe plan intern au fost suspendate |last=Bulgakov, Kadi |date=13 March 2020 |website=Realitatea Sportiv\u0103}}</ref> The rugby match between Romania and Belgium, to be held in [[Boto\u0219ani]] on 14 March, was postponed by [[Rugby Europe]].<ref name=\"ziare\" /> The [[IWF Junior World Weightlifting Championships]] in [[Bucharest]], scheduled for 14\u201321 March, have been cancelled.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://realitateasportiva.net/o-competitie-sportiva-din-romania-anulata-din-cauza-epidemiei-de-coronavirus/ |title=O competi\u021bie sportiv\u0103 din Rom\u00e2nia, anulat\u0103 din cauza epidemiei de coronavirus |last=Iona\u0219cu, Andrei |date=2 March 2020 |website=Realitatea Sportiv\u0103}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{commons category-inline|COVID-19 pandemic in Romania}}\n* [https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/#countries Confirmed cases and deaths by country, territory, or conveyance] (worldometer)\n* [https://instnsp.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/5eced796595b4ee585bcdba03e30c127 Interactive map with confirmed cases, people in quarantine, isolated people, etc.] (ArcGIS)\n* [https://covid19.geo-spatial.org/dashboard/main Maps and statistics on the situation of COVID-19 pandemic in Romania] (geo-spatial.org)\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|Romania|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Romania]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Romania]]\n[[Category:February 2020 events in Europe]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in Europe]]\n[[Category:2020 in Romania]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe|Romania]]\n", "name_user": "GX, May 1971", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSport", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Romania"}
{"title_page": "Cate Blanchett on screen and stage", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian actress}}\n{{use Australian English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n[[File:Cate Blanchett (6795459727).jpg|thumb|Blanchett at the [[1st AACTA Awards]]]]\n[[Cate Blanchett]] is an [[Australians|Australian]] actress who has appeared extensively [[Film|on screen]] and [[Theatre|on stage]]. She made her stage debut in 1992 by playing [[Electra]] in the [[National Institute of Dramatic Art]] production of [[Electra (Sophocles play)|the same name]].<ref>{{cite web|title=A date with Cate |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/1999/apr/18/anthonyminghella |first=Anthony |last=Minghella |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=18 April 1999 |accessdate=19 May 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150919163002/http://www.theguardian.com/film/1999/apr/18/anthonyminghella |archivedate=19 September 2015 }}</ref><ref name=\"newyorker\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2007/02/12/disappearing-act |title=The Evolution of Cate Blanchett |website=The New Yorker |accessdate=17 May 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160915041652/http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2007/02/12/disappearing-act |archivedate=15 September 2016 }}</ref> She followed it with performances in [[Timothy Daly (playwright)|Timothy Daly]]'s ''Kafka Dances'' (1993) and the [[Sydney Theatre Company]] stage production of ''[[Oleanna (play)|Oleanna]]'' (1993), opposite [[Geoffrey Rush]].<ref name=\"newyorker\"/> Blanchett won the [[Sydney Theatre Awards|Sydney Theatre Critics Award]] for Best Newcomer for the former, and Best Actress for the latter, making her the first person to win both awards at once.<ref name=\"newyorker\"/> She went on to perform several roles on stage, notably Susan Traherne in ''[[Plenty (play)|Plenty]]'' (1999), Hedda Gabler in ''[[Hedda Gabler]]'' (2004), [[Blanche DuBois]] in ''[[A Streetcar Named Desire]]'' (2009), Yelena in ''[[Uncle Vanya]]'' (2011), and Claire in ''[[The Maids]]'' (2013).<ref name=\"stage\">{{cite web|title=Cate Blanchett Before Broadway: 5 Memorable Stage Roles|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/cate-blanchett-before-broadway-5-memorable-stage-roles-963309/item/plenty-blanchett-before-broadway-963304|first=David|last=Rooney|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=13 January 2017|accessdate=19 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nBlanchett's first leading role on television came with ''[[Heartland (Australian TV series)|Heartland]]'' (1994), and she followed it with the miniseries ''[[Bordertown (1995 TV series)|Bordertown]]'' (1995).<ref name=\"afi\">{{cite web|title=Cate Blanchett to receive Australia\u2019s highest screen Award |url=https://au.tv.yahoo.com/shows/aactas/a/30291570/cate-blanchett-to-receive-australias-highest-screen-award/ |publisher=[[Yahoo!]] |date=7 December 2015 |accessdate=18 May 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160223083811/https://au.tv.yahoo.com/shows/aactas/a/30291570/cate-blanchett-to-receive-australias-highest-screen-award/ |archivedate=23 February 2016 }}</ref> In 1997, she made her feature film debut in a supporting role in the [[World War II]] drama ''[[Paradise Road (1997 film)|Paradise Road]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cate Blanchett: Cate The Great |url=http://www.marieclaire.com/celebrity/a181/cate-blanchett/ |first=Cleo |last=Glyde |work=[[Marie Claire]] |date=10 January 2017 |accessdate=19 May 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906025926/http://www.marieclaire.com/celebrity/a181/cate-blanchett/ |archivedate=6 September 2015 }}</ref> The same year, she had her first leading role in ''[[Oscar and Lucinda (film)|Oscar and Lucinda]]'', which earned her an [[Australian Academy of Cinema and Television Arts|AACTA Award]] nomination for Best Actress.<ref name=\"afi\"/><ref name=\"great\">{{cite web|title=The Essentials: 5 Great Cate Blanchett Performances|url=http://www.indiewire.com/2013/07/the-essentials-5-great-cate-blanchett-performances-95612/|publisher=[[IndieWire|Indiewire]]|date=23 July 2013|accessdate=18 May 2017}}</ref> Blanchett received worldwide attention for playing [[Queen Elizabeth I of England]] in the acclaimed drama ''[[Elizabeth (film)|Elizabeth]]'' (1998).<ref name=\"rt\">{{cite web|title=Cate Blanchett |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/celebrity/cate_blanchett |publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=18 May 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170221210528/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/celebrity/cate_blanchett |archivedate=21 February 2017 }}</ref><ref name=\"meta\">{{cite web|title=Cate Blanchett |url=http://www.metacritic.com/person/cate-blanchett?filter-options=movies&page=1 |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=18 May 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150110042859/http://www.metacritic.com/person/cate-blanchett?filter-options=movies |archivedate=10 January 2015 }}</ref> Her performance garnered her a [[Golden Globe Award|Golden Globe]] and a [[BAFTA Awards|BAFTA Award]] for Best Actress, and her first [[Academy Award]] nomination for Best Actress.<ref name=\"afi\"/> ''Elizabeth'' and her next film, the thriller ''[[The Talented Mr. Ripley (film)|The Talented Mr. Ripley]]'' (1999), performed well at the box office. However, her other 1999 releases{{mdash}}the widely praised ''[[An Ideal Husband (1999 film)|An Ideal Husband]]'' and the largely panned ''[[Pushing Tin]]''{{mdash}}were unsuccessful.<ref name=\"rt\"/><ref name=\"meta\"/><ref name=\"bo\">{{cite web|title=Cate Blanchett Movie Box Office Results |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/people/chart/?id=cateblanchett.htm |publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=18 May 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202015219/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/people/chart/?id=cateblanchett.htm |archivedate=2 February 2017 }}</ref>\n\nBlanchett found greater success for portraying [[Galadriel]] in [[Peter Jackson]]'s epic fantasy trilogy ''[[The Lord of the Rings (film series)|The Lord of the Rings]]'' (2001{{ndash}}2003).<ref name=\"afi\"/> She won the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress]], among other honors, for portraying [[Katharine Hepburn]] in [[Martin Scorsese]]'s 2004 drama ''[[The Aviator (2004 film)|The Aviator]]'', making her [[List of Academy Award records#Miscellaneous records|the only actor to win]] an Oscar for portraying another Oscar-winning actor.<ref name=\"afi\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Cate Blanchett on \"How to Train Your Dragon 3\" and the Fear of Oscar Speeches |url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/cate-blanchett-how-to-train-your-dragon-3-oscar-speeches-1201430186/ |first=Tim |last=Gray |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=10 February 2015 |accessdate=19 May 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160830110832/http://variety.com/2015/film/news/cate-blanchett-how-to-train-your-dragon-3-oscar-speeches-1201430186/ |archivedate=30 August 2016 }}</ref> Her only screen appearance in 2005 was in ''[[Little Fish (2005 film)|Little Fish]]'', for which she won the [[AACTA Award for Best Actress in a Leading Role|AACTA Award for Best Actress]].<ref name=\"afi\"/> Blanchett's performance in the 2006 thriller ''[[Notes on a Scandal (film)|Notes on a Scandal]]'' garnered her another Academy Award nomination for Best Supporting Actress.<ref name=\"academy\">{{cite web|title=How Many Oscars Has Cate Blanchett Won? The 'Carol' Actor Is An Academy Favorite |url=https://www.bustle.com/articles/134269-how-many-oscars-has-cate-blanchett-won-the-carol-actor-is-an-academy-favorite |first=Katherine |last=Cusumano |work=[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]] |date=13 January 2016 |accessdate=18 May 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160524160703/http://www.bustle.com/articles/134269-how-many-oscars-has-cate-blanchett-won-the-carol-actor-is-an-academy-favorite |archivedate=24 May 2016 }}</ref> In 2007, she received both Best Actress and Best Supporting Actress Oscar nominations for her roles in ''[[Elizabeth: The Golden Age]]'' and ''[[I'm Not There]]'', becoming [[List of actors nominated for two Academy Awards in the same year|one of the few actors to achieve this feat]].<ref name=\"academy\"/>\n\nIn 2008, Blanchett appeared in [[Steven Spielberg]]'s action adventure ''[[Indiana Jones and the Kingdom of the Crystal Skull]]'' and in [[David Fincher]]'s fantasy drama ''[[The Curious Case of Benjamin Button (film)|The Curious Case of Benjamin Button]]''.<ref name=\"rt\"/><ref name=\"meta\"/> She briefly reprised her role of Galadriel in ''[[The Hobbit (film series)|The Hobbit trilogy]]'' (2012{{ndash}}2014).<ref name=\"great\"/> For her performance as the titular socialite in [[Woody Allen]]'s 2013 drama ''[[Blue Jasmine]]'', Blanchett won the Golden Globe, the BAFTA Award, the [[SAG Award]], and the [[Academy Award for Best Actress]].<ref name=\"afi\"/> In 2014, she voiced Valka in the $620 million-grossing animated fantasy ''[[How to Train Your Dragon 2]]'' and its 2019 sequel ''[[How to Train Your Dragon: The Hidden World]]''.<ref name=\"bo\"/> In 2015, she received praise for playing [[Lady Tremaine]] in [[Disney]]'s live action film ''[[Cinderella (2015 Disney film)|Cinderella]]'', [[Mary Mapes]] in ''[[Truth (2015 film)|Truth]]'', and the titular character in [[Todd Haynes]]'s romantic drama ''[[Carol (film)|Carol]]''.<ref name=\"bo\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Cate Blanchett's 10 best movies |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/film/what-to-watch/cate-blanchett-best-roles/ |first=Tim |last=Robey |work=The Telegraph |date=15 October 2015 |accessdate=18 May 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160815134221/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/film/what-to-watch/cate-blanchett-best-roles/ |archivedate=15 August 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Review: Disney's live-action Cinderella rekindles old studio magic |url=http://time.com/3743894/cinderella-review-disney-live-action/ |last=Corliss |first=Richard |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date=13 March 2015 |accessdate=18 May 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222180408/http://time.com/3743894/cinderella-review-disney-live-action/ |archivedate=22 February 2017 }}</ref> ''Cinderella'' was a notable box office success, while ''Carol'' garnered her seventh Oscar nomination.<ref>{{cite web|title=Forget the Ball, \"Cinderella\" Is the Belle of the Box Office |url=http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/03/15/forget-the-ball-cinderella-is-the-belle-of-the-box-office/ |last=Barnes |first=Brooks |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=15 March 2015 |accessdate=24 December 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150908065415/http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/03/15/forget-the-ball-cinderella-is-the-belle-of-the-box-office/ |archivedate=8 September 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Why Did Carol Get Shut Out of Oscar's Biggest Categories? |url=http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2016/01/carol-shut-out-best-picture-best-director |work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |first=Richard |last=Lawson |date=14 January 2016 |accessdate=8 February 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160203161129/http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2016/01/carol-shut-out-best-picture-best-director |archivedate=3 February 2016 }}</ref> Blanchett made her Broadway debut in 2017 with ''[[Platonov (play)|The Present]]'', receiving her first [[Tony Award]] nomination for the [[Tony Award for Best Actress in a Play|Best Actress in a Play]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Tony Awards 2017 Nominations: Cate Blanchett, Bette Midler, and More Get Nods |url=http://www.indiewire.com/2017/05/tony-awards-2017-nominations-cate-blanchett-bette-midler-laura-linney-1201811592/ |first=Jude |last=Dry |publisher=IndieWire |date=2 May 2017 |accessdate=18 May 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170506062411/http://www.indiewire.com/2017/05/tony-awards-2017-nominations-cate-blanchett-bette-midler-laura-linney-1201811592/ |archivedate=6 May 2017 }}</ref> In 2017, she assumed the role of primary villain in the film ''[[Thor: Ragnarok]]'' as Hela. The following year, Blanchett starred in ''[[Ocean's 8]]'', the all-female spin-off of the [[Ocean's Trilogy|''Ocean's Eleven'' franchise]], directed by [[Gary Ross]], and the Eli Roth-helmed film, ''[[The House with a Clock in Its Walls (film)|The House with a Clock in Its Walls]]''.\n\n==Film==\n<!--DO ''not'' USE ROWSPANS per WP:FILMOGRAPHY-->\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Key\n| style=\"background:#FFFFCC;\" | {{dagger|alt=Films that have not yet been released.}}\n| Denotes films that have not yet been released.\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"| Year\n!scope=\"col\"| Title\n!scope=\"col\"| Role\n!scope=\"col\"| Director(s)\n!scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n!scope=col class=\"unsortable\" | {{abbr|Refs.|Reference(s)}}\n|-\n! scope=row | 1996 \n| ''[[Parklands (film)|Parklands]]''\n| Rosie\n|{{sort|Millard|Kathryn Millard}}\n|[[Short film]]\n|style=\"text-align: center;\"|<ref>{{cite web|title=Parklands (1996)|url=https://www.moviefone.com/movie/parklands/747/main/|publisher=[[Moviefone]]|accessdate=19 May 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n! rowspan=\"3\" scope=\"row\" | 1997\n|''[[Paradise Road (1997 film)|Paradise Road]]''\n| {{sort|Macarthy|Susan Macarthy}}\n| {{sort|Beresford|[[Bruce Beresford]]}}\n|\n|style=\"text-align: center;\"|<ref>{{cite web|title=Paradise Road (1997) |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/paradise_road |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=17 May 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170210214601/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/paradise_road/ |archivedate=10 February 2017 }}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Thank God He Met Lizzie]]''\n| Lizzie\n| {{sort|Nowlan|[[Cherie Nowlan]]}}\n|\n|style=\"text-align: center;\"|<ref>{{Cite news|title=Review:\u2018Thank God He 